  <!-- ═══ RISKS ═══ -->
  <h2>Risks & Limitations</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Debt Burden:</strong> NRG carries substantial debt (${(debt/1000).toFixed(1)}B), which makes the equity value highly sensitive to interest rate changes and refinancing risks.</li>
    <li><strong>Capital Intensity:</strong> As a utility, NRG requires massive ongoing capital expenditures. If our normalized FCF assumption underestimates future maintenance capex, the true intrinsic value is lower.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Risk:</strong> Utilities operate in heavily regulated environments. Unfavorable rate case outcomes or changes in energy policy can directly impact profitability.</li>
    <li><strong>Commodity Prices:</strong> Exposure to natural gas and wholesale electricity prices can create volatility in cash flows despite hedging efforts.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the raw FCF deeply negative?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">NRG has recently made massive capital expenditures (e.g., ~$10.9B in the recent year), likely related to acquisitions (like Vivint Smart Home) or major infrastructure buildouts. Standard FCF subtracts all capex from operating cash flow. For a DCF to work, we must normalize FCF to represent the recurring cash generation of the core business, stripping out one-time mega-capex.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why use an 8% discount rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Utilities are generally less volatile than the broader market (lower beta). An 8% WACC reflects a reasonable required return for a stable, dividend-paying utility in a 4.18% 10-Year Treasury environment.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical model. Intrinsic value models are highly sensitive to assumptions, especially the normalization of cash flows and the discount rate. Conduct your own due diligence.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

